if (Use_kegg) {
  Column_of_interest = 47
} else {
  Column_of_interest = 44
}

dim_raw = dim(gene_df)[1]
gene_df = gene_df[,c(2:35,Column_of_interest)]

## Computing relative abundance
for (i in 1:34){
  sum_col = sum(gene_df[,i])
  if (sum_col != 0){
    gene_df[,i] = gene_df[,i]/sum_col
  }
}


if (Use_kegg) {
  gene_df = separate_rows(gene_df,all_of( \KEGG_ko\), sep = \

The relative abundances are then computed.

<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZ2VuZV9kZiA9IGFnZ3JlZ2F0ZShnZW5lX2RmWy0xXSwgYnkgPSBsaXN0KGdlbmVfZGYkR2VuZSksIEZVTiA9IHN1bSlcbmNvbG5hbWVzKGdlbmVfZGYpWzFdID0gXFxHZW5lXFxcblxuZ2VuZV9uYW1lcyA9IGxldmVscyhnZW5lX2RmJEdlbmUpICMjIFNhdmluZyB0aGUgbGlzdCBvZiBnZW5lcyBuYW1lcyBmb3IgbGF0ZXJcbmhlYWQoZ2VuZV9kZilcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
gene_df = aggregate(gene_df[-1], by = list(gene_df$Gene), FUN = sum)
colnames(gene_df)[1] = \Gene\

gene_names = levels(gene_df$Gene) ## Saving the list of genes names for later
head(gene_df)

library(reshape2)

melted_data = melt(cor_data, id = \metabolites\) ## Melting the data.frame

melted_data = drop_na(melted_data) ## Removing empty columns
melted_data$metabolites = as.factor(melted_data$metabolites) 
colnames(melted_data)[2] = \genes\

## Removing genes in metabolite column and reverse.
melted_data = subset(melted_data, metabolites %in% metabo_names & genes %in% gene_names)
melted_data = droplevels.data.frame(melted_data)

rm(list=c(\cor_data\))

# Filtering metabolites and genes

## Filtering on correlation values

In order to do that, we filter the `melted_data` data frame to keep rows if the correlation value is more than the threshold or less than the negative threshold.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxudGhyZXNfa2VlcCA9IDAuNlxuXG5maWx0ZXJlZF9tZWx0ZWRfZGF0YSA9IG1lbHRlZF9kYXRhICU+JSBzdWJzZXQobWVsdGVkX2RhdGEkdmFsdWUgPD0gLXRocmVzX2tlZXAgfCBtZWx0ZWRfZGF0YSR2YWx1ZSA+PSB0aHJlc19rZWVwKVxuXG5maWx0ZXJlZF9tZWx0ZWRfZGF0YSA9IGRyb3BsZXZlbHMuZGF0YS5mcmFtZShmaWx0ZXJlZF9tZWx0ZWRfZGF0YSlcblxucm0obGlzdD1jKFxcbWVsdGVkX2RhdGFcXCkpXG5oZWFkKGZpbHRlcmVkX21lbHRlZF9kYXRhKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
thres_keep = 0.6

filtered_melted_data = melted_data %>% subset(melted_data$value <= -thres_keep | melted_data$value >= thres_keep)

filtered_melted_data = droplevels.data.frame(filtered_melted_data)

rm(list=c(\melted_data\))
head(filtered_melted_data)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

```r
```r
selected_genes = levels(filtered_melted_data$genes)
selected_metabo = levels(filtered_melted_data$metabolites)

tmp_data = data[,c(selected_genes, selected_metabo)]

library(\psych\)
## suppressWarnings is here to not show warnings about standard deviation being null (which slows down the function)
cor_res = suppressWarnings(corr.test(tmp_data[,-1], method = \spearman\, ci = F))
cor_pval = as.data.frame( cor_res$p )
cor_pval$metabolites <- rownames(cor_pval)
cor_pval = cor_pval[c(dim(cor_pval)[2], 1:(dim(cor_pval)[2])-1)]

melted_pval = melt(cor_pval, id = \metabolites\) ## Melting the data.frame

melted_pval = drop_na(melted_pval) ## Removing empty columns
melted_pval$metabolites = as.factor(melted_pval$metabolites) 
colnames(melted_pval)[2] = \genes\

melted_pval = subset(melted_pval, metabolites %in% metabo_names & genes %in% gene_names)
colnames(melted_pval)[3] = \pvalue\
melted_pval = droplevels.data.frame(melted_pval)

filtered_melted_pval = subset(melted_pval, pvalue >= 0.05) # Keeping only significative results

rm(list=c(\melted_pval\, \tmp_data\))
head(filtered_melted_pval)

filtered_melted_data_ordered = order(filtered_melted_data[,-c(1,2)], decreasing = TRUE)
filtered_melted_data = filtered_melted_data[filtered_melted_data_ordered[1:100],]

ggplot(filtered_melted_data, aes(gene, metabolite, fill= value)) +
  geom_tile(colour = \white\, size = 0.5)+
  scale_fill_gradientn(name = \Correlation coefficient\,# definition of the color gradient.
                       #trans = \log10\, #chosing a logarythmic color scale
                       breaks = c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5 ,1), 
                       labels = c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5 ,1),
                       #na.value = \#43A3B9\,# plotting the 0 in the lowest color of the gradient
                       colours = c(\#43A3B9\,  \#D0EC97\, \#FFFFDF\, \#FD945D\, \#DC4E51\, \#370303\),
  )+
  
  scale_x_discrete(expand=c(0, 0))+ # Removing blank space between data and X axis
  labs(fill=\correlation coefficient\, # Setting legend and title name
       title = \Correlation coefficients between genes and metabolites\)+
  theme_grey(base_size=12)+ # Setting the base font size
  theme(line = element_blank(), # Removing the lines in between the boxes
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(), # Removing ticks on X axis
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, face=\bold.italic\, size = 30), # Removing X labels
        axis.text.y = element_text(face=\bold.italic\, size = 30), # Setting Y labels to bold
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), # Removing X axis title
        axis.title.y = element_blank(), # Removing Y axis title
        panel.border=element_blank(), # Removing space between figure and panel
        legend.text=element_text(face=\bold\, size = 15), # Customizing legend font
        plot.title = element_text(face=\bold\, size = 50), # Same with main title
        legend.title = element_text(face=\bold\, size = 15), # Same with legend
        legend.key.size = unit(2, \cm\), # Setting the legend scale
        strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, face = \bold\, size = 15),
        strip.text.x = element_text( face = \bold\, size = 15))

## Loading libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(hrbrthemes)

## Setting the X and Y columns to show
x_col = \VPS13\
y_col = \glucosamine-6-phosphate\

##
ggplot(data, aes(x = data[,x_col]*100, y = data[,y_col]*100))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = \red\, se = F, show.legend = T)+
  labs(title = paste0(\Correlation graph between \, x_col, \ and \, y_col),
       x = paste0(\Relative abundance of \, x_col,\ (%)\),
       y = paste0(\Relative abundance of \, y_col,\ (%)\))+
  theme_grey(base_size=12)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face=\bold\, size = 15))
